TY  - JOUR
AU  - Goldberg, Matthew S.
T1  - Discrimination, Nepotism, and Long-Run Wage Differentials*
PY  - 1982
Y1  - 1982/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/1880760
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 97
IS  - 2
SP  - 307
EP  - 319
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The wage discrimination model developed by Becker has been criticized for predicting that competitive forces will lead to the disappearance of racial discrimination in the long run. We have reformulated the model in terms of nepotism toward white workers rather than discrimination against black workers. In this new framework, both nepotistic and taste-neutral firms are expected to survive the competitive struggle in the long run. Therefore, the new framework is consistent with long-run as well as short-run racial wage differentials.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1880760
ER  - 



